#Frequency of crimes committed inside or outside.

data['Inside/Outside'] = data['Inside/Outside'].replace('I', 'Inside')
data['Inside/Outside'] = data['Inside/Outside'].replace('O', 'Outside')

data1_io = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['Inside/Outside','Total Incidents','District'])

df_inside = data1_io[data1_io['Inside/Outside'] == "Inside"].groupby(['District'],as_index=False).count()

df_outside = data1_io[data1_io['Inside/Outside'] == "Outside"].groupby(['District'],as_index=False).count()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(17,7))
width = 0.3

ax.bar(df_outside.iloc[:,0], df_outside.iloc[:,2], width,  label='Outside')
ax.bar(df_outside.iloc[:,0], df_inside.iloc[:,2], width,  bottom=df_outside.iloc[:,2], label='Inside')

ax.set_ylabel('Crime Frequency')
ax.set_title('Frequency of Crimes committed inside or outside')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

Above graph represents number of insode and outside crimes by each district. Districts like central and southeatsern had more outside crimes than inside from 2012 to 2017. Whereas northeastern district had more inside crimes than outside. All other districts had approximately same amount of inside and outside crimes from 2012 to 2017.

#Derived Date,Day,Month,Year,Weekday and Hour from columns CrimeDate and CrimeTime.

data['CrimeTime'] = data['CrimeTime'].str.replace('24:00:00', '00:00:00')
data['Date'] = data['CrimeDate'] + ' ' + data['CrimeTime']

data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'])
data['Day'] = data['Date'].dt.day
data['Month'] = data['Date'].dt.month
data['Year'] = data['Date'].dt.year
data['Weekday'] = data['Date'].dt.weekday + 1
data['Hour'] = data['Date'].dt.hour

def generateBaseMap(default_location = [39.30364, -76.6139599], default_zoom_start = 12):
    base_map = folium.Map(location = default_location, control_scale = True, zoom_start = default_zoom_start)
    return base_map

base_map = generateBaseMap()
data_murder = data[data['Description'] == 'HOMICIDE']

HeatMap(
        data = data_murder[['Latitude', 'Longitude']].groupby(
            ['Latitude', 'Longitude']).sum().reset_index().values.tolist(),
        radius = 8,
        max_zoom = 13).add_to(base_map)

from matplotlib.collections import QuadMesh
from matplotlib.text import Text
import numpy as np

#Manipulating data to feed pivot table to then feed to seaborn heatmap
incidents_wh = data.groupby(['Weekday', 'Hour'])['Total Incidents'].sum()
incidents_wh = incidents_wh.reset_index(level=[0,1]) # to go from mutlindex to singleidnex
pivoted_table = incidents_wh.pivot(index='Hour', columns='Weekday', values='Total Incidents')
pivoted_table.fillna(0, inplace=True)

#Select max value from the data
max_value = pivoted_table.max().max()

#Create sum for rows and columns
pivoted_table.loc['Total'] = pivoted_table.sum()
pivoted_table = pd.concat([pivoted_table,pd.DataFrame(pivoted_table.sum(axis=1),columns=['Total'])],axis=1)

#Generate heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8), dpi=60)
ax = sns.heatmap(pivoted_table, cmap='Reds', annot=True, fmt='g', annot_kws={'size': 9}, vmax=max_value)


#Set white color to total column and row
# find your QuadMesh object and get array of colors
quadmesh = ax.findobj(QuadMesh)[0]
facecolors = quadmesh.get_facecolors()

# make colors of the last column white
column_number = pivoted_table.shape[1]
cells_number = pivoted_table.shape[0]*pivoted_table.shape[1]
last_row = pivoted_table.shape[1]*(pivoted_table.shape[0]-1)

facecolors[np.arange(column_number-1,cells_number,column_number)] = np.array([1,1,1,1]) #change column total to white
facecolors[np.arange(last_row, cells_number,1)] = np.array([1,1,1,1]) #change row total to white

# set modified colors
quadmesh.set_facecolors = facecolors

# set color of all text to black
for i in ax.findobj(Text):
    i.set_color('black')
 
#Labels
labels = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday',' Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday', 'Total']
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.xaxis.tick_top()
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.title('Number of incidents by weekday and hour for years 2012-2017', fontsize=16, y=1.05)
plt.xlabel('Incident weekday', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('Incident hour', fontsize=16);

1.There were less crimes commited at night hours between 2 A.M. and 6 A.M. 2.Crimes were more often commited at late hours like 17 P.M and 18 P.M 3.Friday is day with the most commited crimes 4.There were more incidents at hours 12 A.M to 3 A.M. The reason may be a weekend when people spend more time out of home and are drunk 5.Saturday and Sunday are days when crimes are commited the least.

In [227]:
#Convert Description,IO and Weapon to categorical variables.

KNN_data["Description"] = pd.factorize(KNN_data.Description)[0]
KNN_data["IO"] = pd.factorize(KNN_data.IO)[0]
KNN_data["Weapon"] = pd.factorize(KNN_data.Weapon)[0]

X = np.array(KNN_data.iloc[:,0:6])
y = np.array(KNN_data['Description'])

# split the data into the train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20)

knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=100)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
pred = knn.predict(X_test)

print ('\nModel accuracy score: ', accuracy_score(y_test, pred))

print('\nConfusion Matrix\n', confusion_matrix(y_test, pred))

In [228]:
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,pred)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 7))

sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,fmt='',cmap='Blues')

ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels');
ax.set_ylabel('True labels'); 
ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix');

Confusion matrix consist of Predicted values and actual values for target variables. From above confusion matrix , 8010 number denotes TRUE POSITIVE cases for category 3. For example, if we consider category 3 is Common Assault then 8010 is number of crimes are correctly classified as Common Assault from our model. FALSE POSITIVE value for column 3 will be sum of all the values in column 3 except TRUE POSITIVE(8010). FALSE NEGATIVE value for column 3 will be sum of all the values of row 3 except TRUE POSITIVE(8010) and TRUE NEGATIVE is all the remaining values in the confusion matrix except TRUE POSITIVE,FALSE POSTIVE and FALSE NEGATIVE.

#Fitting In RandomForest Ensemble
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
rfc = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=40,min_samples_split=100 )
rfc.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Predicting The Final Results
rfc_pred = rfc.predict(X_test)
print ("Train Accuracy: ", accuracy_score(y_train, rfc.predict(X_train)))
print ("Test Accuracy: ", accuracy_score(y_test, rfc_pred))

Train Accuracy:  0.7908575069790023
Test Accuracy:  0.776928211663329

Accuracy of model using KNN classification was 68%. To improve the accuracy we used more optimized machine learning method i.e. Random Forest Method. In Random Forest Method, tree value (estimators) is 40 and accuracy of model improved to 77%.
